english:
  title: Colophon to the Hundred Houses Garment Collection
  author: Nam Sumuun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Once upon a time, Wang Jingong passed by the study of Su Dongpo and spotted an ancient inkstone upon the desk. Struck with admiration, he declared, "I shall compose a poem by gathering verses from the ancients." Immediately he began: "A skillful craftsman carves the mountain's bone—" But there he paused, lost in contemplation, unable to continue to the end.

    Consider this: even Wang Jingong, possessed of such superior talent and vast learning, struggled with the art of gathering verses. How much more difficult, then, for those of lesser gifts!

    Yet Master Lin, Sacrificial Official of Goryeo, has compiled his Hundred Houses Garment Collection—three scrolls containing more than two hundred eighty poems in five and seven-character forms. The sources he drew from are beyond counting. Gathering verses from a hundred poets, he flows left and right with inexhaustible resourcefulness, and whether encountering stones or clouds, his brush composes. His parallel couplets achieve such precision that they seem the work of Heaven itself—as if one had taken the silks of Yue and the brocades of Shu and, through masterful needlework, wove five colors into harmonious brilliance that dazzles both heart and eye.

    Such wealth of memory, such genius in weaving fragments into wholeness—surely even Wang Jingong, beholding this work, would willingly defer!

    Though this collection was once carved into blocks at Gyeongju, time wore the plates away, and people copied it by hand to preserve it. In the autumn of the Zhengong jiawu year, the Provincial Inspector Lee, Prime Minister of Gaesong, procured the printed edition from the library of the Gyeongyon and had it newly carved and distributed from Andong. Thus not only does Master Lin's name endure undimmed, but his patron's noble heart—his love of antiquity and his devotion to exalting the good—shines forth still more brightly to all future ages.
  footnotes:
    - The anecdote about Wang Anshi and Su Shi illustrates the extreme difficulty of 'gathered verse' composition, where poets assemble lines from classical works to create new poems.
    - The 'Hundred Houses Garment Collection' (百家衣集) refers to a collection of poems created through this gathering technique; the metaphor of silk and brocade suggests the varied textures and colors of the assembled verses.
